In the JSFiddle, it is showing &#39;IM NOT CLOSE&#39; because the last element is larger than 0.05

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    let distance = [0.004996111561227907, 14.897649343418598, 5654.180955177425]

    for (i = 0; i &lt; distance.length; i++) {
      if (distance[i] &lt; 0.05) {   // one of them are true
        console.log(&#39;IM CLOSE!!&#39;);
        break;
      }
    }
    if (i === distance.length) {  // all of them are false
      console.log(&#39;IM NOT CLOSE&#39;);
    }

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

The issue is that your loop doesn&#39;t exit once it finds a `true` case. It evaluates every single element in the array and updates the text accordingly. As a result, the text will always correspond to the *last item in the array*. In this case, that item is NOT &quot;close&quot;.

To exit the loop, use [`break`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Statements/break):

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: true console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    let distance = [0.004996111561227907, 14.897649343418598, 5654.180955177425]

    for (i = 0; i &lt; distance.length; i++) {
      if (distance[i] &lt; 0.05) {
        $(&#39;#phrase&#39;).text(&#39;IM CLOSE!!&#39;)
        break;  //  &lt;--------------------------- EXIT THE LOOP
      } else {
        $(&#39;#phrase&#39;).text(&#39;IM NOT CLOSE&#39;)
      }
    }

